\f0\fs24 \cf0 \expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 The placement of "DESI" on the H0DN figure is genuinely interesting and worth thinking carefully about, because 
\f1\b DESI in cosmology is doing two completely different things at the same time
\f0\b0  \'97 and only one of them is what's labeled in the H0DN figure.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa298\partightenfactor0

\f1\b\fs36 \cf0 DESI: the basic facts\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\fs24 \cf0 DESI = Dark Energy Spectroscopic Instrument
\f0\b0  \'97 a multi-object spectrograph mounted on the 4m Mayall Telescope at Kitt Peak National Observatory, run by an international collaboration (~900 members, lead institutions LBNL, Berkeley, NOIRLab). The instrument has 5,000 robotically positioned fibers covering a 3.2\'b0 field of view, capable of obtaining spectra of 5,000 galaxies/QSOs simultaneously. Operations began in 2021; the survey is planned through 2026 with possible extensions.\
Survey design: ~40 million spectra over ~14,000 deg\'b2, covering redshifts 0 < z < 3.5 across multiple target classes:\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\ls1\ilvl0
\f1\b \cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 BGS
\f0\b0  (Bright Galaxy Survey): ~10
\f2 \uc0\u8311 
\f0  galaxies at 0 < z < 0.4\
\ls1\ilvl0
\f1\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 LRG
\f0\b0  (Luminous Red Galaxies): ~8 \'d7 10
\f2 \uc0\u8310 
\f0  at 0.4 < z < 1.0\
\ls1\ilvl0
\f1\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 ELG
\f0\b0  (Emission Line Galaxies): ~1.7 \'d7 10
\f2 \uc0\u8311 
\f0  at 0.6 < z < 1.6\
\ls1\ilvl0
\f1\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 QSO
\f0\b0 : ~3 \'d7 10
\f2 \uc0\u8310 
\f0  quasars at 0.6 < z < 3.5\
\ls1\ilvl0
\f1\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Ly\uc0\u945  forest
\f0\b0 : derived from QSO continuum at z > 2.1\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0
\cf0 This sample is ~10\'d7 larger than SDSS BOSS, the previous-generation spectroscopic survey, and represents the largest 3D map of the universe ever constructed.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa298\partightenfactor0

\f1\b\fs36 \cf0 DESI's two cosmological roles\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0\fs24 \cf0 DESI in cosmology pursues two largely independent measurement programs, both of which yield H
\f2 \uc0\u8320 
\f0  but in completely different ways:\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f1\b \cf0 Role 1: Baryon Acoustic Oscillations (BAO).
\f0\b0  This is what DESI is famous for and what most cosmologists mean when they say "DESI." BAO measurements use the characteristic ~150 Mpc clustering scale imprinted on the matter distribution at recombination as a 
\f1\b standard ruler
\f0\b0  seen in the galaxy distribution at z = 0.1 to 2.3. Combined with CMB measurements of the sound horizon, BAO gives H
\f2 \uc0\u8320 
\f0  in a way that's mostly independent of the SN Ia distance ladder. DESI's flagship BAO results (Adame+24 / DESI-DR1, +25 / DESI-DR2) are headline cosmology and are the basis for the recent claims of dynamical dark energy.\

\f1\b Role 2: Peculiar Velocity Survey (PVS) via Fundamental Plane.
\f0\b0  This is the more obscure but H0DN-relevant program. DESI's BGS sample includes ~10
\f2 \uc0\u8310 
\f0  early-type galaxies at z < 0.15 \'97 the largest FP sample ever constructed. Said+25 applies the Fundamental Plane to this sample, anchored via SBF and TRGB, to derive H
\f2 \uc0\u8320 
\f0  from the local velocity field. This is what's labeled "DESI" on the H0DN figure.\
The two roles produce H
\f2 \uc0\u8320 
\f0  values that are conceptually different objects:\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\ls2\ilvl0
\f1\b \cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 BAO H
\f3 \uc0\u8320 
\f0\b0  is a CMB-anchored measurement of "the H
\f2 \uc0\u8320 
\f0  that \uc0\u923 CDM would need to fit the BAO+CMB data." This is essentially Planck-side; it lands at ~67\'9668 km/s/Mpc.\
\ls2\ilvl0
\f1\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 FP/PVS H
\f3 \uc0\u8320 
\f0\b0  is a local Hubble-flow measurement of "what's the actual expansion rate at z < 0.15." This is firmly local-side; it lands at ~76 km/s/Mpc.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0
\cf0 These are the same physical quantity (H
\f2 \uc0\u8320 
\f0 ) measured by methodologically opposite approaches. Their disagreement is essentially the H
\f2 \uc0\u8320 
\f0  tension itself, exposed within a single survey.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa298\partightenfactor0

\f1\b\fs36 \cf0 Why "DESI" on the H0DN figure means specifically the PVS/FP measurement\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0\fs24 \cf0 The H0DN paper is a 
\f1\b local-distance-network
\f0\b0  paper. It's about measurements of H
\f2 \uc0\u8320 
\f0  from the cosmic distance ladder out to ~30,000 km/s. BAO and CMB measurements of H
\f2 \uc0\u8320 
\f0  are not in scope. So when the figure shows "DESI" as a labeled route, it's referring to the FP-based PVS measurement, not the BAO-based H
\f2 \uc0\u8320 
\f0  value.\
The specific reference (Said et al. 2025) is the canonical DESI FP paper:\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f1\b \cf0 Said et al. 2025
\f0\b0 , "Cosmological Parameters from the DESI Peculiar Velocity Survey," reports H
\f2 \uc0\u8320 
\f0  = 76.05 \'b1 0.35 (stat) \'b1 1.5 (sys) km/s/Mpc using ~6 \'d7 10
\f2 \uc0\u8309 
\f0  FP-distance ETGs. The FP zero point is calibrated via the SBF distance scale (which is itself anchored via TRGB and the maser distance to NGC 4258), so the chain is:\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0
\cf0 NGC 4258 maser 
\f4 \uc0\u8594 
\f0  TRGB in Fornax/Virgo 
\f4 \uc0\u8594 
\f0  SBF zero point 
\f4 \uc0\u8594 
\f0  FP zero point 
\f4 \uc0\u8594 
\f0  DESI FP distances to ~10
\f2 \uc0\u8310 
\f0  ETGs 
\f4 \uc0\u8594 
\f0  Hubble flow 
\f4 \uc0\u8594 
\f0  H
\f2 \uc0\u8320 
\f0 \
This is structurally similar to what we discussed for CF4 (TF-dominated, ~10
\f2 \uc0\u8308 
\f0  galaxies, 75 \'b1 3) but with two important upgrades: (1) FP instead of TF, (2) ~50\'d7 more galaxies, (3) much better-controlled spectroscopic calibration because all spectra come from the same instrument with the same observing protocol.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa298\partightenfactor0

\f1\b\fs36 \cf0 Why DESI FP is potentially transformative\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0\fs24 \cf0 A few features of DESI FP that make it qualitatively different from CF4 FP:\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f1\b \cf0 1. Sample size.
\f0\b0  ~6 \'d7 10
\f2 \uc0\u8309 
\f0  usable FP galaxies, vs ~3 \'d7 10
\f2 \uc0\u8308 
\f0  in 6dFGS (the previous flagship FP sample). This is roughly a 20\'d7 sample increase, which translates to ~4-5\'d7 better statistical precision 
\f5\i if
\f0\i0  systematics are controlled.\

\f1\b 2. Spectroscopic homogeneity.
\f0\b0  All velocity dispersions measured with the same instrument, same fiber size, same exposure protocol, same data reduction pipeline. This essentially eliminates the inter-survey calibration systematics that plague heterogeneous compilations like 6dFGS+SDSS+GAMA.\

\f1\b 3. Photometric homogeneity.
\f0\b0  DESI imaging uses the DESI Legacy Imaging Surveys, which provide consistent multi-band photometry across the full survey area. Effective radii and surface brightnesses are extracted with a uniform pipeline.\

\f1\b 4. Per-galaxy precision.
\f0\b0  With ~24% per-galaxy distance scatter (typical for FP) and 6 \'d7 10
\f2 \uc0\u8309 
\f0  galaxies, the formal statistical precision on H
\f2 \uc0\u8320 
\f0  approaches 0.5%. The realistic systematic floor \'97 calibration zero point, peculiar velocity model, FP slope variations across galaxy types \'97 sits at ~2%.\

\f1\b 5. The systematic is now SBF-anchored.
\f0\b0  This is the cleanest part of DESI FP. The FP zero point used to be calibrated via Cepheid-distance galaxies (when only a few SN Ia hosts had FP measurements), which introduced Cepheid-related systematics. DESI FP is calibrated via SBF, which is in turn anchored via TRGB and NGC 4258. So DESI FP is structurally part of the 
\f1\b Pop-II network
\f0\b0 , not the Pop-I/Cepheid network.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa298\partightenfactor0

\f1\b\fs36 \cf0 DESI FP in the H0DN landscape\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

