\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0
\cf0 DESI FP at 76 sits at the 
\f1\b high end of the local-H
\f3 \uc0\u8320 
\f1  cluster
\f0\b0 . It's the highest-central-value measurement on the figure, and at \'b11.5 it has the second-best precision after SH0ES.\
This is unusual and worth being explicit about: 
\f1\b DESI FP is a precision-competitive measurement that disagrees with SH0ES at ~2\uc0\u963  on the high side
\f0\b0 . Most of the H
\f2 \uc0\u8320 
\f0  debate has focused on the SH0ES vs Planck disagreement (~5\uc0\u963  on the low side), but DESI FP introduces a smaller but non-trivial disagreement on the 
\f5\i other
\f0\i0  side. DESI FP and SH0ES both prefer high H
\f2 \uc0\u8320 
\f0 , but DESI FP prefers it ~3 km/s/Mpc higher than SH0ES.\
If this disagreement holds up \'97 and it might evolve as Said+25's systematic budget gets refined over the next 2\'963 years \'97 it's its own minor "tension" worth understanding. Possible explanations include:\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\ls3\ilvl0
\f1\b \cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	1	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 SBF zero point too high.
\f0\b0  If the TRGB
\f4 \uc0\u8594 
\f0 SBF calibration is biased high by ~3%, DESI FP would inherit that bias. This is plausible at the few-percent level.\
\ls3\ilvl0
\f1\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	2	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 PV model imperfect.
\f0\b0  DESI FP applies bulk-flow corrections; if the local PV field has features not captured in the model, this propagates to H
\f2 \uc0\u8320 
\f0 . ~1 km/s/Mpc effect.\
\ls3\ilvl0
\f1\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	3	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 FP slope or zero-point variation across galaxy populations.
\f0\b0  If the FP coefficients differ between cluster-core and field ETGs, and DESI samples them differently from the calibrating SBF galaxies, this introduces a systematic.\
\ls3\ilvl0
\f1\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	4	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 The high value is correct, and other methods are slightly low.
\f0\b0  This is the less likely interpretation but not impossible.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa298\partightenfactor0

\f1\b\fs36 \cf0 DESI BAO H
\f3 \uc0\u8320 
\f1  \'97 the 
\f6\i other
\f1\i0  DESI measurement\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0\fs24 \cf0 For completeness, since you'll encounter the DESI BAO H
\f2 \uc0\u8320 
\f0  values in EDE work too:\
DESI's BAO-derived H
\f2 \uc0\u8320 
\f0  (from DESI-DR2 + Planck) is ~67.4 \'b1 0.5 \'97 essentially identical to Planck alone. This is because BAO + CMB tightly constrain the cosmological parameters in \uc0\u923 CDM, and H
\f2 \uc0\u8320 
\f0  is the inferred quantity given the model. 
\f1\b In \uc0\u923 CDM
\f0\b0 , BAO + CMB always give H
\f2 \uc0\u8320 
\f0  \uc0\u8776  67.\
But here's where it gets interesting for your EDE work: DESI-DR2 finds 
\f1\b mild evidence (~3\uc0\u963 ) for dynamical dark energy
\f0\b0 , with the equation-of-state parameter w(z) preferring w
\f2 \uc0\u8320 
\f0  ~ -0.8, w_a ~ -0.7 (instead of the cosmological constant w = -1). If you allow w to evolve, the BAO + CMB inferred H
\f2 \uc0\u8320 
\f0  shifts upward modestly.\
This couples directly to EDE inference in a non-trivial way:\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\ls4\ilvl0
\f1\b \cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	1	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 EDE shifts the sound horizon at recombination
\f0\b0 , which propagates to BAO interpretation. So BAO measurements at z = 0.1\'962.3 are not independent of EDE \'97 they're sensitive to it through the BAO standard ruler calibration.\
\ls4\ilvl0
\f1\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	2	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 DESI-DR2's mild w(z) preference might be partly absorbed by EDE.
\f0\b0  Some recent papers (e.g., Wang+25, Lin+25) have argued that EDE models can fit DESI-DR2 BAO without requiring dynamical late-time dark energy, by shifting the recombination-era sound horizon.\
\ls4\ilvl0
\f1\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	3	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 The combined CMB + DESI BAO + SH0ES likelihood prefers EDE
\f0\b0  at the few-\uc0\u963  level. This is essentially the strongest current statistical evidence for EDE in the literature.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0
\cf0 For your fluid-vs-axion comparison, DESI BAO data (specifically DESI-DR2's full power spectrum + BAO measurements) is one of the 
\f5\i primary
\f0\i0  discriminators between fluid and axion implementations. Different EDE models predict different shifts in the recombination-era sound horizon and different post-recombination perturbation behavior, and DESI's z = 0.5 to 2.3 BAO data are sensitive to both.\
So DESI plays two roles in your EDE work:\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f1\b \cf0 Role A: DESI FP local H
\f3 \uc0\u8320 
\f1  (Said+25, 76 \'b1 1.5)
\f0\b0  \'97 feeds into your local-H
\f2 \uc0\u8320 
\f0  likelihood, sits at the high end of the local cluster, contributes to the structural argument that the H
\f2 \uc0\u8320 
\f0  tension is real.\

\f1\b Role B: DESI BAO (DR2, full power spectrum)
\f0\b0  \'97 feeds into your CMB+LSS likelihood, where it acts as a primary discriminator between fluid-EDE and axion-EDE. This is where your fluid-vs-axion model preference is actually being decided.\
Note that Role A and Role B are statistically nearly independent. The DESI FP sample (z < 0.15) and the DESI BAO sample (z = 0.4-3.5) come from different target classes (BGS vs LRG/ELG/QSO), are analyzed by different working groups within DESI, and use different methodologies. So you can include both as independent likelihoods without significant covariance concerns.\
